overhang.translation[0].definitions[0].d: to hang over something or stick out above it
overhang.translation[1].definitions[0].d: a rock, roof etc that hangs over something else
overhang.translation[1].definitions[0].e: We stood under the overhang while it rained.
overhang.translation[1].definitions[1].d: the amount by which something hangs over something else
overhang.translation[2].definitions[0].d: to have a bad influence on something
overhang.translation[2].definitions[0].e: Currency worries overhung many engineering stocks.
overhang.translation[2].definitions[1].d: if a large quantity of something overhangs the market, it has not been sold when it should have been and therefore has a negative influence on prices
overhang.translation[2].definitions[1].e: There is not a huge surplus overhanging the market.
overhang.translation[3].definitions[0].d: an unsold quantity of something that has a bad influence on prices, markets etc
overhang.translation[3].definitions[0].e: The huge overhang of world-wide crude oil inventories further depressed energy prices.
As long as there is a supply overhang silver will do poorly.
